Preliminary notes

This document details the pipeline used in the Rasplus et al paper for the assembly of forward (R1 or reads1) and reverse (R2 or reads2) reads and to retrieve RAD loci from genome of outgroup species.
The pipeline has been designed by J.-Y. Rasplus and A. Cruaud and written by AC.
Most parts of the pipeline were written for a Linux server (Ubuntu 15.10; Dell PowerEdge T630 server with two 10-core Intel(R) Xeon(R) CPUs E5-2687W v3 @ 3.10GHz) and some were written for a SLURM cluster controller.
Were are not professional bioinformaticians yet we try to do our best! So, the code will not appear clean to purists (apologize for that) and there are certainly other ways to reach the same goal !

Source code for scripts mentioned in the pipeline are in https://github.com/acruaud/radseq_ficus_2019. The scripts were written by M. Gautier and modified by AC.

Goal and warnings

Note: This pipeline is written to work with the results provided by the wrapper RADIS that relies on Stacks for the building of RAD loci from forward reads, but it can be used directly on Stacks results, provided that:
  • the correct paths to files /scripts are given,
  • R1 and R2 are named with the same string of characters and the suffix _1 or _2 (e.g.R1 name = @8_1101_1942_1994_1 /R2 name = @8_1101_1942_1994_2),
  • a list of cstacks locus ids is provided which is simply a list of numbers (when you use RADIS the list is in a stacks_M$Mn$nS$SL$L.sel file). 
    • #example of a list of cstacks locus ids
head -n 10 stacks_M2n20S56L100.sel  
3
9
17
24
27
33
    Goals: Starting from a list of cstacks locus ids (reads1 only loci), assembly of reads1 and reads2 to increase length of loci to:
    1. enable a more accurate calculation of locus properties and a better selection of loci to decrease potential bias in phylogenetic inference,
    2. retrieve RAD loci in outgroups for which restriction sites have been lost because of divergence.
    Attention:
  • You need to adapt path to your own file tree structure and change filenames if needed.
  • You need to edit the retrieve_read2ids.awk script to change path to the sel_fq_2.awk script.
  • You may need to make script executable before use: chmod +x scriptname
  • Our sample codes are formatted as follows: AlphanumericCode_NumericCode (e.g JRAS01331_0001). Some parts of the pipelines (statistics) may fail if you do not use the same format (StringOfCharacters_StringOfCharacters), adapt cmd to your case and check that you obtain the desired output before moving to the next step.

    • External resources

    Some parts of the pipeline require the following softwares /scripts (or equivalents):
  • catfasta2phyml: for the concatenation of all loci into a supermatrix.
  • Fasta2Phylip.pl: to convert fasta to phylip.
  • Geneious: for visualization of sequences (version used = 11.1.4).
  • Lastz: for alignment of DNA sequences to reference genomes (version used = 1.02.00).
  • MAFFT: for locus by locus alignment (version used = 7.313).
  • samclip: to remove sequences with hard /soft clipped unaligned ends from sam files.
  • samtools: to work with .sam files (version used = 1.9 with htslib 1.9).
  • Sequence-manipulation: to build consensus sequence from non overlaping fasta.
  • trimal: to remove alignment position with 100% gaps (version used = v1.4.rev22 build[2015-05-21]).
  • Trinity: for the assembly of forward and reverse reads (version used = 2.3.2).

    • Reference genomes

  • The genome of Ficus carica, assembly GCA_002002945.1, was used for the alignment of contigs of forward and reverse reads.
  • The genomes of Morus notabilis GCA_000414095.2 and Artocarpus camansi GCA_002024485.1, the only two other Moraceae species for which a genome was available when we conducted the study were screened for RAD loci.

    • Pipeline

    Part One: Assembly of reads1 and reads2 and confirmation of sequence homology

    Step 1: from a list of cstacks locus ids retrieve forward and corresponding reverse reads

    Unzip fq_2.gz files for the samples included in your analysis.
    If you used RADIS the files are stored in the 04_PUR subdirectory-ies of the outdir_datacleaning directory(ies).

    for i in *fq_2.gz
do 
gunzip $i
done

    Create a datadir for your analysis and cd to datadir.

    cd /home/cruaud/rad_ficus/outdir_dataanalysis_m15M2n20S56L100/M2/NO_PBLOCI-3/n20_03_SEL   #here we create our datadir in the output directory of RADIS where the R1 loci were built
mkdir assembly_reads1reads2   #and my datadir will be named assembly_reads1reads2
cd assembly_reads1reads2
    Create symbolic links (to keep space) or copy $sample_code.fq_1 (=fastq files that contain the reads1 for each sample included in your analysis) and $sample_code.fq_2 (=fastq files that contain the reads2 for each sample included in your analysis) files to datadir.
    The samples we studied come from 2 libraries, so we execute the command twice with 2 different paths.
  • reads1 
    • ls /home/cruaud/articles/rad_ficus/lib1/outdir_datacleaning/PBC/04_PUR/*.fq_1 |awk '{print "ln -s "$1}' | bash
ls /home/cruaud/articles/rad_ficus/lib2_reseq/outdir_datacleaning/PBC/04_PUR/*.fq_1 |awk '{print "ln -s "$1}' | bash
  • reads2 
    • ls /home/cruaud/articles/rad_ficus/lib1/outdir_datacleaning/PBC/04_PUR/*.fq_2 |awk '{print "ln -s "$1}' | bash
ls /home/cruaud/articles/rad_ficus/lib2_reseq/outdir_datacleaning/PBC/04_PUR/*.fq_2 |awk '{print "ln -s "$1}' | bash

    Create a file that lists all *.tags.tsv files created by ustacks + their path.

    ls ../../../01_TAGS/*tags.tsv > batch_1.files

    Execute the retrieve_ustacks_ids.awk script to get, for each sample, the list of ustacks loci merged in the different cstacks loci.
    Provide a list of cstacks locus ids (here a .sel file generated by RADIS) and the corresponding cstacks catalog.tags.tsv as input.

    #run the script
gawk -f /home/cruaud/programs/rad/retrieve_ustacks_ids.awk batch_1.files ../stacks_M2n20S56L100.sel ../../../02_CATALOG/batch_20.catalog.tags.tsv

#Output = retrieve_ustacks_ids.out
#column1 = cstacks locus id
#column2 = path to $sample_code.tags.tsv file
#column3 = locus id in sample.tags.tsv file

    Execute the retrieve_read2ids.awk script to get, for each sample, the list of reads2 ids to retrieve and a script file to retrieve them.
    Attention: Do not forget to edit the retrieve_read2ids.awk script to change path to the sel_fq_2.awk script before running.
    Provide a list of cstacks locus ids (here a .sel file generated by RADIS), the retrieve_ustacks_ids.out created in the previous step and the path to ustacks *tags.tsv files as input.

    /home/cruaud/programs/rad/retrieve_read2ids.awk ../stacks_M2n20S56L100.sel retrieve_ustacks_ids.out ../../../01_TAGS/*tags.tsv

#Output 1 = $sample_code.read2.lst    #as many files as the number of samples are created 
#column1 = read2 ids
#column2 = cstacks locus id 

#Output 2 = retrieve_read2.run #that contains a list of commands to retrieve reads2 from $sample_code.fq_2 files with the sel_fq_2.awk script

    Make executable and execute the retrieve_read2.run file created at the previous step to retrieve reads2 in fq_2 files.

    chmod +x retrieve_read2.run
./retrieve_read2.run

#Output = $sample_code.fq_2.sel    #as many files as the number of samples are created 
#the output is a fastq file with 3 extra columns added to each line
#column1 = cstacks_locus_id 
#column2 = $sample_code.fq_2 
#column3 = line_number_in_$sample_code.fq_2    #to facilitate sorting

    Retrieve corresponding reads1:

    1. Convert $sample_code.read2.lst files into $sample_code.read1.lst files
    for i in *.read2.lst
do
sed s/"_2 "/"_1 "/g $i > $i".read1.lst"
done
    1. Rename output files (clean extension).
    rename s/"\.read2\.lst"/""/g *.read1.lst
    1. Convert retrieve_read2.run script into retrieve_read1.run.
    sed s/"read2"/"read1"/g retrieve_read2.run |sed s/"fq_2"/"fq_1"/g > retrieve_read1.run
    1. Make executable and execute retrieve_read1.run.
    chmod +x retrieve_read1.run
./retrieve_read1.run

    Sort the resulting .sel files for reads1 and reads2.

    for i in *.sel
do
sort -k2,2 -k3,3 -k4n,4n $i > $i.sort
done

#Output = $sample_code.fq_1.sel.sort and $sample_code.fq_2.sel.sort 
#as many files as the number of samples are created and reads are now sorted by cstacks locus ids (column2 of the files)

    Use the parse_fq_sel.pl script to split $sample_code.fq_$i.sel.sort files into $cstackslocusid_$sample_code.fq_1 and .fq_2 files and store all resulting files in a subdirectory.

    for i in *sel.sort
do
/home/cruaud/programs/rad/parse_fq_sel.pl --inputfile $i --outputdir assembly    #here the output directory name will be "assembly" but you can change it if you like
done

#Output = .fastq files which are stored in the assembly directory
#output filenames = cstackslocusid_$sample_code.fq_1 and cstackslocusid_$sample_code.fq_2

    Cleaning to save space.
    You can remove all files with the exception of the assembly" directory, or you may keep the symbolic links and batch_1.files if you need to re-run analyses.

    rm *.sel *.sort *.lst retrieve_ustacks_ids.out retrieve_read*.run

    End of step 1: For all samples included in your analysis, and all selected cstacks loci, you should now have fastq files for forward and reverse reads in the assembly directory


    Step 2: assembly of forward and reverse reads

    We use Trinity but you may use your favorite assembler

    Replace the last occurrence of _1 by /1 in *fq_1 files for trinity assembly.

    for i in *.fq_1
do
sed -i 's/\(.*\)_1/\1\/1/' $i
done

    Replace the last occurrence of _2 by /2 in *fq_2 files for trinity assembly.

    for i in *.fq_2
do
sed -i 's/\(.*\)_2/\1\/2/' $i
done

    For the alignment we switch to the Genologin SLURM cluster to decrease computation time with increased parallel execution.
    List your samples.

    ls *.fq_1 |sed s/"\.fq_1"/""/g > mysamples.txt

    Prepare cmd file.

    awk '{print "#!\/bin\/bash\n#SBATCH -J trinity\n#SBATCH -p workq\n#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=4\n#SBATCH -t 02:00:00\n\nmodule load bioinfo\/trinityrnaseq-v2.3.2\nmodule load bioinfo\/bowtie2-2.2.9\n\nTrinity --seqType fq --left "$1".fq_1 --right "$1".fq_2 --output trinity_"$1" --full_cleanup --CPU 4 --max_memory 2G --min_contig_length 100"}' mysamples.txt > tmp_cmd 

#nota: --min_contig_length should be lower or equal to the length of your R1 RAD loci, if not, contigs of R1 will not be retained by trinity

    Split the cmd file into as many scripts as the number of samples (trinity_xx.sh scripts will be created).

    awk '/#!/{filename="trinity_"NR".sh"}; {print >filename}' tmp_cmd

    Run all scripts (as many scripts as the number of samples will be submitted).

    for i in trinity_*.sh
do
sbatch $i
done

#output = trinity_$samplecode.Trinity.fas

    When all jobs are over, check that everything ran properly

    ls *.Trinity.fasta |wc -l    #should be equal to the number of samples you wanted to assemble reads for

    Note: You should have at least one contig for each sample (at least a contig of reads1). If there are some samples for which no assembly is produced, we suggest to perform assembly in Geneious.


    Once the assembly is finished, we upload all trinity contigs to our personal Linux server in a new assembly/trinity directory and go back to our server.
    So, cd to datadir.

    cd assembly/trinity

    Compute some statistics.

    #number of contigs per sample
grep -c ">" trinity_* |sed s/"trinity_"/""/g |sed s/"_fq\.fa\.Trinity\.fasta:"/";"/g > nbcontigs_persample.txt
#average contig length
for i in trinity_*
do
echo $i >> averagecontiglength.txt && grep "len=" $i |awk '{print $2}' |sed s/"len="/""/g |awk '{S+=$1}END{print S/NR}' >> averagecontiglength.txt  ####Nota: the mean is biased by the short size of the read1 when there is no overlap between R1 and R2
done

    Rename contigs in trinity files.

    for i in trinity_*
do
awk 'BEGIN{i=1} {if (/^>/) {print ">Contig"i; i++} else print $0}' $i > $i".contigs"
done

    Trash original files.

    rm *.fasta

    Remove the trinity_ prefix from filenames.

    rename s/"trinity_"/""/g *.contigs

    Rename contig headers in trinity.fasta.contigs => headers will look like >1015_$sample_code_Contig1.

    ls *.Trinity.fasta.contigs |sed s/"\.Trinity\.fasta\.contigs"/""/g |awk -F - '{print "sed -i -e \047s/^>/>"$1"_/g\047 "$0"\.Trinity\.fasta\.contigs"}' |bash

    End of step 2: For all samples included in your analysis, and all selected cstacks loci, you should now have contig(s) of R1+R2.
    Note that if you should have at least one contig per sample (at least a contig of reads1) you may have more than one contig per sample in cases where contigs (R1 vs R2 or several contigs of R2) do not overlap.


    Step 3: alignment of contigs to reference genome
    Here we will use the genome of F.carica to align the contigs of R1+R2.

    Create a fasta file for each cstacks locus:
    Note that in each locus file you may have more than one contig per sample in cases where contigs did not overlap.

    1. create datadir in assembly.
    mkdir alignment
    1. copy trinity contigs to datadir.
    cp trinity/*.Trinity.fasta.contigs alignment
cp geneious/*.geneious.fasta.contigs alignment
    1. cd to datadir.
    cd alignment
    1. create and execute cmd to concatenate contigs for all samples in one file per locus.
    ls *.Trinity.fasta.contigs |awk -F"_" '{print $1}' |sort |uniq |awk '{print "cat "$0"_* > locus_"$0".fasta"}' |bash
#output = locus_$cstackslocusid.fasta
    1. cleaning.
    rm *.Trinity.fasta.contigs
    1. count loci.
    ls locus_*.fasta |wc -l   #should be equal to the number of expected loci

    Align loci to the genome of Ficus carica:
    Again, we switch to the Genologin SLURM cluster to decrease computation time with increased parallel execution.
    Thus, we copy all locus_*.fasta files in a empty directory of the cluster.
    We will use the software Lastz but you may use another alignment software.
    FYI below is the script we use to run Lastz on the SLURM cluster:

    #!/bin/sh
#SBATCH -J lastz
#SBATCH -p workq
#SBATCH -t 1:00:00

module load bioinfo/lastz-1.04.00
lastz /home/acruaud/save/genome_ref/GCA_002002945.1_F.carica_assembly01_genomic.fna[multiple,unmask] $1[unmask] --gapped --format=softsam --ambiguous=iupac --output=$1".vs_genomecarica.sam"

    and how we run it on all samples:

    for i in locus_*.fasta
do
sbatch lastz_vs_carica.sh $i
done

    Then we copy all output .sam files to our Linux server in the alignment directory.
    End of step 3: For each cstacks locus, you should now have a .sam files that show alignment results from all contigs of all samples.


    Step 4: parsing of alignment results
    The goal of this step is to create a summary file with the results of the alignment step to enable a proper selection of RAD loci in the next step.
    Good RAD loci are loci for which we have good arguments suggesting that the contigs obtained for each sample are homologous (i.e.we try to confirm or not hypotheses of homology made by ustacks /ctacks).
    Our life is easier here as we included a sample of F.carica in our RAD library (sample code = JRAS06927_0001). So we can compare our empirical results to the reference genome for a more appropriate selection of loci.

    Remove contigs with hard+soft clipped unaligned ends > 10 bp from sam files (with samclip).

    for i in *.sam
do
/home/cruaud/programs/samclip/samclip --ref /home/cruaud/articles/rad_ficus/reprise_july2019/genomes/GCA_002002945.1_F.carica_assembly01_genomic.fna --max 10 < $i > $i".clip10"
done

    Record if a sequence of F.carica JRAS06927_0001 is present in the locus or not.

    for i in locus_*.fasta
do
echo $i >> tmp_carica && if grep -q "JRAS06927" $i; then echo "carica"; else echo "no_carica"; fi >> tmp_carica
done

awk 'NR % 2 == 1 { o=$0 ; next } { print o ";" $0 }' tmp_carica |sort > tmp_carica2

    Count the number of initial contigs in the locus*.fasta files.

    for i in locus_*.fasta
do
echo $i >> tmp_stat && grep -c ">" $i >> tmp_stat
done

awk 'NR % 2 == 1 { o=$0 ; next } { print o ";" $0 }' tmp_stat > tmp_stat2

    Count the number of contigs that have an alignment hit on the reference genome.

    for i in *.sam.clip10
do
awk '{if (!/^@/) {print $3}}' $i |sort |uniq -c |sort -nr >> "tmp_stat_sam_"$i
done

for i in tmp_stat_sam_locus_*
do
awk '{print FILENAME";"$0}' $i > "tmp2_"$i
done

sed -i -e 's/; */;/g' tmp2_*

sed -i s/" "/";"/g tmp2_*

sed -i s/"tmp_stat_sam_"/""/g tmp2_*

sed -i s/"\.vs_genomecarica\.sam\.clip10"/""/g tmp2_*

cat tmp2_* >> tmp_stat_sam_allhits

    Record the genome scaffold with the highest number of hits.
    we assume that this scaffold likely contains the RAD locus [it may not be always true but we will control that later].

    for i in tmp2_*
do
head -n 1 $i > "tmp1_"$i
done

cat tmp1_* >> tmp_stat_sam_mostfrequenthit

    Join all resulting files into an intermediate statistic file (statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt) to make locus selection easier.

    join -t ";" -a 1 -e "NA" -o 1.1,2.2,1.2,1.3 tmp_stat_sam_mostfrequenthit tmp_stat2 > tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt
join -t ";" -a 1 -e "NA" -o 1.1,1.2,1.3,1.4,2.2 tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt tmp_carica2 > tmp_tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt
# add "warning" if number of contigs that aligned with the target > number of initial contigs
awk -F";" '{if($3>$2) {print $0";warning"} else print $0";ok"}' tmp_tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt > tmp_tmp_tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt
# add headers
awk 'BEGIN{print "cstacks_locus;nb_contigs;nb_hits_on_target;target;carica;warning_more_contigs_in_outfile"} {print $0}' tmp_tmp_tmp_statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit.txt > statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt

#final output = statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt
#this file is an intermediate file, the final file will be created in the next step
#column 1 = ctacks locus name
#column 2 = number of contigs available for the locus
#column 3 = number of contigs that hit genome region
#column 4 = genome region
#column 5 = carica JRAS06927_0001 present or not: "carica"" or "no_carica""
#column 5 = carica JRAS06927_0001 present or not: "ok" if carica present "warning" if not present

    Cleaning.

    rm tmp*

    Reduce sam files to the genome scaffold that likely contains the RAD locus.

    #prepare script
awk -F";" '{if(NR>1) {print "grep \042"$4"\042 "$1".vs_genomecarica.sam.clip10 |awk \047BEGIN{print \042@HD\\tVN:1.0\\tSO:unsorted\042} {print $0}\047 > "$1".vs_genomecarica.sam.clip10.red"}}' statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt > reduce_sam.sh
# make executable and execute script (output file extension = .red)
chmod +x reduce_sam.sh
./reduce_sam.sh 
# cleaning
rm reduce_sam.sh

    Check if F.carica JRAS06927_0001 is still present in the resulting .red files.

    for i in *.red
do
echo $i >> tmp_carica_in_red && if grep -q "JRAS06927" $i; then echo "carica"; else echo "no_carica"; fi >> tmp_carica_in_red
done

awk 'NR % 2 == 1 { o=$0 ; next } { print o ";" $0 }' tmp_carica_in_red |sort > tmp_carica_in_red2

    Add this info to the statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt file.

    sed -i s/"\.vs_genomecarica\.sam\.clip10\.red"/""/g tmp_carica_in_red2
awk '{if (NR>1) {print}}' statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10.txt > tmp_stat
join -t ";" -a 1 -e "NA" -o 1.1,1.2,1.3,1.4,1.5,1.6,2.2 tmp_stat tmp_carica_in_red2 > tmp_stat_2

    Compare column carica present in initial and in final file to produce a warning message.

    awk -F";" '{if ($5!=$7) {print $0";carica_lost"} else print $0";ok"}' tmp_stat_2 > tmp_stat_3

    Add headers and generate final statistics file.

    awk 'BEGIN{print "cstacks_locus;nb_contigs;nb_hits_on_target;target;carica;warning_more_contigs_in_outfile;carica_in_red;carica_lost"} {print $0}' tmp_stat_3 > statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt

#final file = statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt
#column1 = cstacks locus id
#column2 = number of R1+R2 contigs for this locus (for all samples)
#column3 = maximum number of hits found on the reference genome
#column4 = id of the genome region for which we had the highest number of hits which is considered as a first approximation as the most probable RAD locus
#column5 = JRAS06927_0001 sample of F.carica had a sequence for this locus before alignment and parsing of alignment file: yes = carica ; no = no_carica
#column6 = warning if there are more contigs in the resulting sam file than in the locus file (ok if no warning). This may be due to alignment of contigs on different but (close) genome regions
#column7 = JRAS06927_0001 sample of F.carica present in the alignement file with clip10 and reduced the most probable RAD locus: yes = carica ; no = no_carica
#column8 = we lost JRAS06927_0001 sample of F.carica when we clip10 or when we reduced to the genome region for which we had the highest number of hits: yes = carica_lost; no = ok

#example
head -n 3 statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt
cstacks_locus;nb_contigs;nb_hits_on_target;target;carica;warning_more_contigs_in_outfile;carica_in_red;carica_lost
locus_1003.fasta;97;95;BDEM01000593.1;carica;ok;carica;ok
locus_1017.fasta;113;110;BDEM01000169.1;no_carica;ok;no_carica;ok
locus_1025.fasta;94;216;BDEM01000061.1;carica;warning;carica;ok
#which means, for the first record: for the locus_1003 we had 97 contigs (all samples confounded), the majority of which (95) got a hit on the BDEM01000593.1 genome fragment; the JRAS06927_0001 sample of carica was present in the cstacks locus, there are as many or less contigs in the alignment file than in the original query file, the JRAS06927_0001 sample of carica was still present in the final alignment file reduced to the most probable RAD locus.

    Cleaning.

    rm tmp_*

    End of step 4: you should now have a statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt file that will help you to select homologous RAD loci.


    Step 5: selection of RAD loci and retrieval of the reference sequence in the F. carica genome.
    The goal of this step is to perform selection of loci with the help of the summary file created in the previous step.
    Good RAD loci are loci for which we have good arguments to think that the contigs obtained for each sample are homologous (i.e.we try to confirm or not hypotheses of homology made by ustacks /ctacks).

    Create a new directory in the alignment directory to store loci that will not be retained for downstream analysis.

    mkdir discarded_loci

    Print on screen loci for which i) we have carica JRAS06927_0001 or not because we did not manage to sequence carica RAD loci and ii) we have less or as many sequences that aligned with the reference genome than the number of input contigs.

    grep -v "warning" statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt |grep -v "carica_lost"     ##[509 loci]

    The strategy we used here was to upload sam files in Geneious and export without any further control. We herefater refer to these loci as non-problematic.

    Print on screen loci for which i) we lost carica because of clip10 or because carica did not align with the genome region with the highest number of hits.

    grep "carica_lost" statistics_alignment_vs_genomecarica_mostfrequenthit_clip10_def.txt

    The strategy we used here was to discard these loci not to take any risk, so we:
    Created a sudirectory in discarded_loci to store these loci.

    mkdir discarded_loci/carica_lost
#and then e.g.
mv locus_1255.fasta* discarded_loci/carica_lost

    The strategy we used here was to upload sam files in Geneious and visually check what happens. We hereafter refer to these loci as problematic.

    Below, we provide details on what we have done in Geneious after upload of the .sam files for the problematic and non-problematic loci.

    First, we took a look to the alignment of the problematic loci to keep only the best block:

  • When a sequence of carica JRAS06927_0001 was available:
    1. We kept only the block for which the carica RAD locus had a (almost) perfect match with the reference genome; ie we removed all sequences that did not align with the same genome region as carica.
    2. We reduced the reference sequence to make it fit with the 5 and 3 limit of the block of contigs and saved the new alignment.
  • When a sequence of carica was NOT available:
    1. We kept the block with the highest number of sequences, that started /or ended with (what could have been) a restriction site in the reference genome (ie exact match with sbfI cut site or with one mutation), and that shows the highest identity with the sample contigs.
    2. We reduced the reference sequence to make it fit with the 5 and 3 limits of the block of contigs and saved the new alignment.

    Then, we performed two exports in two different directories: one with the non-problematic loci, one with the problematic loci as follows:

    1. export the alignments as a fasta files.
    2. select all files [except the reference genome if you kept it note that you can trash it to save space] > file > export > batch export > FASTA sequences /alignments > extension .fasta > in the pop-up window: check only the following boxes:
    3. Replace spaces in sequence name with underscores.
    4. Export sequence in upper case.
    5. Export missing ends of alignment as gaps.

  • alignment/cleaning for the non-problematic loci.

    Step 3: parsing of alignment results and homology assessment


    Here, we will count the number of matching bases between the reference loci and the genome.
    We will make the assumption that the genome region with the highest identity is probably the RAD locus.

    Identical bases between the loci and the genome will be changed into =.

#cleaning

#rename final file

awk -F"\t" '{ if (!/^@/) {print $1";"$3";"$4}}' $i > $i.start.pos
done
#cat results into a big file
cat *.start.pos |sort > morus_contigname_startpos.txt
#cleaning
rm *.start.pos
#join genome scaffold name + 5' starting position + length in a file
join -t ";" -a 1 -e "NA" -o 1.1,1.2,1.3,2.2 morus_contigname_startpos.txt reference.length.extended.txt > morus_contigname_startpos_length.txt
#cleaning
rm morus_contigname_startpos.txt
#prepare the list of genome scaffolds in which a match was found
awk -F";" '{print $2}' morus_contigname_startpos_length.txt |sort |uniq > contigs_to_retrieve_in_genome
#prepare, make executable and execute a script to copy required genome scaffolds in datadir
# ATTENTION: genome scaffolds need to be unwrap !!!  
awk '{print "grep -A 1 \042"$0"\042 \/home\/cruaud\/articles\/rad_ficus\/reprise_july2019\/genomes\/GCA_000414095.2_ASM41409v2_genomic_unwrap.fna > "$0"\.fas\.ref"}' contigs_to_retrieve_in_genome > retrieve_genome_contigs.sh

chmod +x retrieve_genome_contigs.sh

./retrieve_genome_contigs.sh
#cleaning
rm retrieve_genome_contigs.sh contigs_to_retrieve_in_genome
#prepare, make executable and execute a script to retrieve loci in genome scaffolds
awk -F";" '{print "awk -F\042 \042 \047{if (/^>/) {print $1} else print substr($0,"$3","$4")}\047 "$2"\.fas\.ref > morus_"$1"\.fas"}' morus_contigname_startpos_length.txt > retrieve_loci_morus.sh

chmod +x retrieve_loci_morus.sh

./retrieve_loci_morus.sh
#rename sequences in output fasta
for i in morus_*.fas
do
awk '{if (/^>/) {print ">genome_morus"} else print $0}' $i > $i.def
done
#record if the locus was aligned in reverse or forward sense
for i in locus*.fillmd
do
awk '{if (!/^@/) {print $1";"$2}}' $i > $i".sense"
done 
#cat results into a big file
cat *.sense |sort > morus_sense_loci.txt
#cleaning
rm morus_*.fas *.fas.ref locus_*.fillmd morus_contigname_startpos_length.txt retrieve_loci_morus.sh *.sense
#rename final files
ls morus_locus_* > tmp_myloci

awk -F"_" '{print "mv "$0" ./"$2"_"$3"_morus.fas.def"}' tmp_myloci |bash

rm tmp_myloci

    End of step 4. You should now have one fasta file for each RAD locus for which a match was found in the target genome.

    Step 5: Time to do some cleaning
    Create a directory to store final and important files.

    mkdir morus
mv locus_*.fas.def morus/  #mv final loci for morus
mv reference.vs_genomemorus.sam morus/  #mv alignment of reference RAD loci on morus genome
mv reference.vs_genomemorus.sam.clip50 morus/ #mv alignment of reference RAD loci on morus genome with clip 50 bp
mv reference.vs_genomemorus.clip50.fillmd morus/  #mv alignment of reference RAD loci on morus genome with clip 50bp and converted to fillmd format 
mv nb_match_referenceclip50_genomemorus morus/   #number of match for the different reference RAD loci on the morus genome with clip 50 bp
mv morus_sense_loci.txt morus/ #to know if the RAD loci match in forward (0) or reverse (16) sense.

    End of step 5. You should feel better now !

    Step 6: Reverse complement loci extracted from genomes if needed
    The idea is to reverse complement the loci that need to be reverse complemented if not mafft alignment will be crazy.


    Prepare, make executable and execute script to reverse complement loci.

    cd morus/

awk -F";" '{split($1,table,"_") ;if($2==16) {print "/home/cruaud/programs/fasta_utilities/scripts/reverse_complement.pl "table[1]"_"table[2]"_morus.fas.def > "table[1]"_"table[2]"_morus.fas.def.rev"}}' morus_sense_loci.txt > reverse_loci.sh

chmod +x reverse_loci.sh

./reverse_loci.sh
#cleaning
rm reverse_loci.sh
#prepare, make executable and execute script remove original sequences for loci that have been reverse complemented
ls locus_* |awk -F"\." '{print $1}' |sort |uniq -c |awk '{if($1>1) {print "rm "$2".fas.def"}}' > remove_original_loci.sh

chmod +x remove_original_loci.sh

./remove_original_loci.sh
#cleaning
rm remove_original_loci.sh
    End of step 6. You should now have 2 kinds of files named as follows.
  • locus_XXX.fas.def when loci were NOT reverse complemented.
  • locus_XXX.fas.def.rev when loci were reverse complemented.
